pageSummary: I am running the David Goggins 4x4x48hr Challenge because of their work looking after cancer patients
pageSummaryWhat: I am running the David Goggins 4x4x48hr Challenge
pageSummaryWhy: of their work looking after cancer patients
rememberedPersonSummary.name: James Bond
story:
To raise awareness around testicular cancer, I have set myself the target of completing the Goggins challenge which is to Run 4 miles every 4 hours for 48 hours.


Cancer will have an impact on most, if not all of us, in our lifetime. For me, it has been twice.¬†When you hear the word 'Cancer,' it generally conjures up negative emotions and feelings.¬† It first impacted me in 1985 when my father passed away from cancer, and then again¬†in 1994 when I was diagnosed with testicular cancer.¬†I still remember even as an 11-year-old the amazing work the nurses did to help my Dad survive as long as he did, and again how the amazing people at Macmillan supported me with my post-treatment care.¬†

They made everyone feel like they were heroes and I'll never forget how much they supported me. This is my way of honoring them and all the hard work they do.¬†It is my goal to raise awareness for one of the most 'taboo' cancers - testicular cancer - which impacts at least 10,000 men aged between 15 and 49 per year globally.

I want to remind all men to check themselves regularly. Prevention is always better than the cure. Seek help if you need it, and do not be embarrassed to ask for help. Life is short, catch it early and you will live a long and fruitful life. I salute all cancer survivors and those who have unfortunately passed. I applaud the battles you face on a daily basis. Mine is but one in a million amongst similar cancer stories. You are all heroes and a source of daily inspiration in my own story,¬†

Thanks for supporting my fundraising. At Macmillan, we give people with cancer everything we‚Äôve got. If you‚Äôre diagnosed, your worries are our worries. We‚Äôre doing whatever it takes. But without your help we can‚Äôt support everyone who needs us.Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

eventName: Cheltenham Preview in aid of Macmillan
owner: Sky Betting and Gaming Macmillan Partnership
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
This year we are taking our staple Cheltenham Preview event to the NEXT LEVEL. Not only will you be hearing the top tips for the Festival from our friends, ITV‚Äôs Ed Chamberlin and Oli Bell, but they will be joined by some¬†very special guest ambassadors¬†from across our UK&I brands‚Ä¶

To add to the fun, we‚Äôre also introducing three virtual horse races (with big prizes for the winners - of which you could be one (see information on ‚Äòowning a horse‚Äô below) and taking the opportunity to fundraise for our Charity Partner of the Year at the same time!

Always fancied owning a race horse
and watching them run in a race? Well now is your chance!¬†

We‚Äôre running three virtual horse
races on the day, as well as one race for our event sponsors (yes, we really are going for it with the fundraising!) The horses running in the virtual horse races will be ‚Äòowned‚Äô and named by you! However we only have 30 places in the races, therefore they will be chosen by a random draw. Entries into the draw are a ¬£5 donation to Macmillan, which can be made via our JustGiving page.

Winners will receive a whopping ¬£500 voucher of your choice - but you have to be in it to win it!

How to enter the draw?

  1. Donate ¬£5 to our Just Giving Page (click here to donate) and in the comments make sure you add the name of your horse.¬†Please submit your entry by COP Friday 5th March to be entered into the draw.¬†
  2. We will draw out names and allocate winning horses to one of the three races.
  3. Join the Cheltenham Preview on Friday 12th March @ 11am to watch your horse run in
    the virtual races and be in with the chance of winning a ¬£500 voucher!
  4. If your horse isn‚Äôt allocated into a race, we of course encourage people to attend
    anyway to join in the fun and raise as much money as possible for our charity
    partner, Macmillan.

Our story

Sky Betting and Gaming's partnership with Macmillan, began in January 2020 and thanks to the generosity of team members and corporate support our fundraising total reached ¬£46,272.14 in the first year, which is amazing given the circumstances. Since our partnership began, team members have thrown themselves into fundraising by hosting a quiz night, donating the cost of morning coffees, holding raffles, bake sales and even decorating boiled eggs to support our partnership! Weve also been running, cycling and walking hundreds of Miles for Macmillan! It doesn't stop there and were going to make 2021 our best year yet! Weve a jam-packed year ahead to raise as much as we can to support people living with cancer. Thank-you Sky Betting and Gaming for helping Macmillan to do whatever it takes, to support people living with cancer.

story:
Our daughter Sienna (3 years old) has asked to do a BIG WALK for Uncle Stevie. 🤍 After much thought, we have signed her up for the EMF Kids Kilometre for Macmillan Cancer Support. 🙌🏼¬†

Our family like many has been deeply affected by Cancer. So this is also in memory of Our Aunt Margret, Cousin Claire and most recently Uncle Stevie who Passed away a year ago today (23.02.20)¬†🤍 Sienna often creates pictures to make Uncle Stevie smile and sings songs to him to make him laugh. She knows that her Uncle Stevie is no longer sore and tired. Sienna tells people that he has went to live with the angels, dinosaurs and Michael Jackson. 👼🏼

She will also join us to complete some of our Walk All Over Cancer Challenge. She has her watch to count her steps.¬†😜 This is the perfect way to ‚Äòtrain‚Äô for her BIG Kilometre Run.¬†

Let‚Äôs Do This! 💟

pageSummary: Rasing money because of support given to our Dad during his final weeks
pageSummaryWhy: of support given to our Dad during his final weeks
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Douglas Abercrombie
story:
After feeling increasingly unwell in the later months of 2020, Dad was suddenly taken to hospital 5 days before Christmas and diagnosed with late-stage Pancreatic Cancer. He spent 9 days in hospital over Christmas and New Year and then was finally allowed home to spend his final weeks with his family in Cupar. Dad sadly died on the 8th of February 2021, aged 67.

He received palliative care for 6 weeks at home from a great team, which included carers, District Nurses, the family GP, Fife Palliative Care team, Marie Curie and Macmillan Cancer support nurses.
We are incredibly grateful for all the care, help and support from these teams and from the staff at Victoria Hospital in Kirkcaldy, particularly those in Critical Care/Surgical HDU wards.

We have chosen to support Macmillan Cancer Support ‚Äì any donations would be greatly appreciated in our Dad‚Äôs memory.

story: This spring, spring clean your health and home to support St John Ambulance. Spring is the season of new beginnings for all. It is slowly getting warmer; the grass is getting a bit greener and the air feels a bit fresher. It is the perfect time of year to have a clean out and to get out! So this Spring why not Spring into Action for St John Ambulance and support our volunteers as they continue to step forward to give vital support to those in need across the country. Since the beginning of the COVID-19 outbreak our volunteers have given an incredible number of hours of support to patients in hospitals across the country, and we are not stopping. Throughout Spring we are continuing to mobilise thousands of volunteers to support the rollout of the COVID-19 vaccination. We need funds to maintain our activities supporting the NHS in our COVID-19 response. The emergency is on-going, and our volunteers will continue to step forward to give vital support. rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Myself and my good friend Dan are ¬†collecting vital funds for the British Heart Foundation, to power pioneering research into heart and cardiovascular diseases. The money we raise will help beat heartbreak forever.¬†

The way we plan on doing this, is by raising money which hopefully will be donated kindly by others. What we are planning ¬†on doing is the 4 by 4 for 48hours. This consists of us running 4 miles every 4 hours for 48hours. This will be a brutal challenge for us both as we are no runners!!¬†

I have been driven to do this for my grandma as she has ¬†recently been diagnosed with heart failure (LVSD). With an ejection fraction of 10% also my girlfriends Grandmother who has had heart surgery and ongoing treatment. If ¬†it wasn‚Äôt for the great work the Heart Foundation carries out ¬† these ¬†very special ladies ¬†may not have been here to witness myself and Dan attempt to complete this challenge.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Babubhai Patel
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story:

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over ¬£100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation by doing thr Marxh Dechix and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. ¬£24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Not only Chocolate but sweets and fizzy drinks too.Thanks!

Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

pageSummary: Hayley Harris QUITS chocolate! üòØ because I‚Äôm doing it for Dave Edwards; and to shed pounds!
pageSummaryWhy: I‚Äôm doing it for Dave Edwards; and to shed pounds!
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Dave Edwards
story:
My two reasons for completing this challenge are;¬†

1. In honour of my lovely friend Angie‚Äôs husband Dave, who devastatingly passed away suddenly last year at a young age. ¬†

2. For myself. ¬†This lockdown has seen me and my lifelong addiction to chocolate increase immensely! I‚Äôm eating ridiculous amounts every night. ¬†I was diagnosed with a heart condition myself many years ago and although it does not affect me day to day currently, my consultant tells me that I will more than likely have to have heart surgery in the future. It‚Äôs crucial that I maintain a healthy eating plan and I need to take action. People who know me will know how incredibly hard this challenge is for me!

Why it is so important that we help the British Heart Foundation: ¬†The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

Every penny helps! The focus currently is all around Covid, and despite this horrific pandemic there are still many people loosing their lives to heart problems! Your support means so much.

Thanks Hayley ‚ù§Ô∏è¬†

pageSummary: I am dechoxing for March because they save lives
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Both my Dad & his wife Julie have gone through life saving emergency heart operations in the last year. ¬†My Dad is still recovering from a triple bypass, Julie had the biggest tumour removed with seconds to spare and is now feeling better than ever! ¬†Without these surgeries, neither of them would be here now. ¬†So, as a total choc-a-holic, I think this is not only something I can do but also something I should do!

I am 50 in February so really no time like the present.¬† Having tried many times to kick my chocolate habit, I hope this is finally it.

I have setup this page to help with my accountability but also to help the BHF in these testing times. ¬†The below paragraph is from them.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
This year in particular many charities are struggling to raise the much needed money to fund research etc.

¬†I know the BHF do such fantastic work and that is why I have decided to help; even if it‚Äôs a little bit .¬†

With that in mind and inspiration of one of my friends who is also doing the same, we are together giving up chocolate, sweets and fizzy drinks!! ...gulp!!¬†

I have lost loved ones from their hearts failing and after a health scare earlier this year it really got me thinking about the importance of keeping as healthy as I can.¬†

We all need to look after our hearts, no matter what age you are.¬†

So I hereby give up all that‚Äôs yummy for ¬†the sake of my heart health. Wish me luck !

If you could spare a ¬£1 or a share of this ¬†donation page I will be very grateful .

Big love from my heart ¬†to you all ‚ô•Ô∏è

story:

I am doing this in the memory of my Grandad Ronald who sadly passed away a few years ago.. He will forever be with us in spirit and memories we made together...

THANKYOU EVERYONE.

story:

story:
Im doing this for my baby Coco!¬†

Cole is such a strong, determined, brave little boy if he can overcome all that he has, me giving up chocolate for a month should be easy!

Cole has was born with Complete Heart Block and had open heart¬†surgery¬†at 5 days old, to have a pacemaker fitted.

When he was 4, he developed heart failure. He had his 2nd open heart surgery a week after his 5th birthday, to have a replacement pacemaker.

Cole is now 8, he'll celebrate his 9th birthday during my "Dechox". His health has improved more than we could have hoped for, he has recovered from heart failure and his heart is functioning within normal range - he's our heart hero!

Cole never complains about having a pacemaker, having check ups or taking his medicine. He makes the whole situation so much easier for us, he's amazing.

Giving up chocolate is the stuff my nightmares are made of! However, the British Heart Foundation is such an important charity ¬†and the research they carry out could change Coles and other children's lives for the better in the future.

Thanks for your support!


The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story:
Come on guys I did it last year and year before.

My dads still not been back to work because of his heart. Anything is better than nothing to help them help people like my dad 😎

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
eventName: Walk, Run or Cycle for Sarah
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story: Thanks for visiting our team fundraising page. We work for Which? and we are fundraising for the British Heart Foundation in memory of our friend and colleague Sarah Price, who passed away suddenly last year at the age of 39. Sarah was a wonderful person; she excelled in her job but was also a committed team-player, going to great lengths to help her team members day-in, day-out. She was a brilliant friend: funny and kind, someone who always made time for everyone she encountered. We continue to miss her greatly. Sarah was a big fan of Welsh rugby and so we are planning to run, walk or cycle a combined distance that will stretch from our Bristol office, where Sarah worked, to the Principality Stadium in Cardiff and back again, which is around 86 miles in total. We plan to do this over the weekend of 27 - 28 February 2021, being the weekend closest to both St. David's Day and Sarah's 5-year anniversary since she started at Which?. Each participant will undertake 5km, either walking, running or cycling, to help us get to the total distance. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to donations that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. ¬£24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help us hit our target. Thanks!

pageSummaryWhat: I am giving up chocolate, sweets and soda
pageSummaryWhy: it's charity and I've overindulged in lockdown!
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Hi all!

Lockdown, Christmas and 2021 for me has meant reaching for the chocolate and enjoying all things sweet. However, not much movement and way too much desk working (and Netflix). March is my challenge month, I am giving up chocolate, sweets and fizzy drinks for 31 days in March. I am also planning to walk 10,000 everyday until 31st March.

If you would like to donate, I will be very grateful. However, I will be more than happy for a cheerleading squad!

Lots of Love,
Sophie x

From BHF

story:
So Ellie, Gemma and I have been running since lockdown last year as a way to keep us fit and sane.

We have decided to attempt the 4x4x48 challenge...more about that below! ITS INSANE! We will try our best to complete it with a combination of runs and power walks. All of this will be documented on social media!

WHAT IS THE 4X4X48 CHALLENGE? (David Goggins)

The 4x4x48 challenge involves running for four miles (6.5km) every four hours for 48 hours. It can be done from anywhere in the world but takes place on a specific date.

It starts on March 5th 2021¬†at 8pm (US Time) and runs for 48 hours.

Our first run will be at Saturday 6th March 2021 at 4am and last will be Monday 8th March at 12am.

We would like to try and fundraise money for the British Heart Foundation as it‚Äôs helped some of our family members in the past.

Any donations will be appreciated we would like to try and fundraise at least ¬£500.

I have decided to try to raise ¬£160.00 to provide a Marie Curie nurse to look after patients in their own homes overnight.

My name is Dr Mark Mills I'm a Doctor who has the pleasure of working at Marie Curie Hospice Liverpool.¬†

I'm part of a dedicated team of professionals and volunteers, who strive to provide excellent care for patients and families with life limiting and terminal health conditions.¬†

Our collective goal is to focus on improving quality of life for our patients and families.¬†

Due to COVID-19 its been increasingly difficult to raise money for the charity and I hope running 200 miles in a month will inspire the public to support in any way they can. My goal is to fund the hospice for a day.¬†

I recently lost my Dad ( Malcolm) due to lung cancer, and he received excellent end of life care.¬† Myself and my family were provided with unbelievable support during this difficult time and I¬† want this to be possible and available for all patients and families.¬†

Any donation no matter how large or small is appreciated and welcomed. I plan to run the 200 miles dressed in bright yellow ( like a daffodil ) so if you see me out and about please stop me and say hello!¬†

story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

eventName: Coulsdon and Purley's Great Daffodil Appeal Collection 2021
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
As Marie Curie's Coulsdon and Purley Fundraising Group, we would normally be gearing up for the Great Daffodil Appeal, getting ready to turn local high streets and supermarkets yellow in our bright hats and tabards, collecting donations in return for daffodil pins. On a regular year like 2019, we raised over ¬£3,840 during the appeal, helping Marie Curie¬†provide over 192 hours of nursing care to terminally ill patients in the¬†local community.¬†

However, it is with a heavy heart that we are unable to hold our usual Great Daffodil Appeal collections this year due to the pandemic.¬†

Last year, Marie Curie saw a 16.5% rise in the number of people they cared for, compared to 2019 and their support line saw a 20% increase in calls too.¬†Right now, more people need Marie Curie than ever before. It is crucial that they¬†are there for them and that they can continue their role in supporting the NHS and¬†relieving the unprecedented pressure they are facing. But just as Marie Curie are needed more than ever, most of their usual fundraising activities¬†remain on hold and they are facing a devastating loss of income.¬†

That‚Äôs why this year we are bringing the Great Daffodil Appeal to you! We would be delighted if you would consider making a donation to our virtual collection bucket, and help ensure that Marie Curie can continue to be there¬†for families in the local community who need their support. Every penny of your donation really will make a huge difference, with every ¬£20 raised funding an hour of nursing care for those who wish to die in the comfort of their own home.¬†

Although we are unfortunately unable to give you a daffodil pin in return for your kind donation, you will receive an email with a link to a downloadable daffodil postcard and a colour-in daffodil, both of which you can display proudly in your window!¬†

Should you have any questions or like to find out about the other ways you can get involved with the Great Daffodil Appeal this year, please contact our Community Fundraiser, Luisa, on Luisa.Stevens1@mariecurie.org.uk


Thank you so much for your support - it really does mean the world to us!

Brian, Chris, Elaine, Jan, Steve and Will (Marie Curie's Coulsdon and Purley Fundraising Group)

story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
This August marks 17 years since my Dad was cared for at a Marie Curie Hospice.¬†

During the last weeks of his life, the Marie Curie Nurses and Doctor provided him with the most amazing care. They ensured that he was comfortable and safe, whilst maintaining his dignity throughout.

¬†As a family, we were able to step back from the practical role of caring for my Dad and simply be his Wife, Daughter and Son. This was priceless.

So, I will taken 10,000 steps each day in March in memory of my Dad and to raise money for this outstanding charity¬†

All donations will be gratefully received¬†

Thank you Lisa x

story:

Marie Curie provided amazing support to Derrick and Jenny and we would like these donations to help provide the same to anyone in a similar situation.

We have also set up a Memories page where you can upload your stories, memories and photos of Derrick, this can be accessed via this link -¬†https://memorycloud.org.uk/tribute/derrick-roy-clarke/

Please feel free to donate as much or as little as you would like - every penny counts!

Thank you XXX

story:
This year, like many, I'll be celebrating my birthday in lockdown so I've decided to raise some money for Marie Curie a charity that has been close to my heart for a number of years and one I have the privilege of working for.¬†

¬£50 pays to stock a hospice drinks trolley, giving people the comfort of their favourite tipple at a time when so much has been taken away for them.

I've pulled together a drinks menu where I'm sure you'll see some of your favourites and asking you to buy a patient a drink in lieu of any birthday¬†drinks or gifts for me.¬†

If you find the menu hard to view please email katie.grinter@mail.com

I‚Äôd like to raise ¬£450 to provide a drinks trolley at each of the 9 Marie Curie hospices.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Cheers!!

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK‚Äôs busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Thank you for visiting our Just Giving Page.

Port Isaac Fundraising Team cover Port Isaac and surrounding areas. Our volunteer fundraisers help to provide the funding to support the lifesaving work of our volunteer lifeboat crews who are available 24/7 for anyone who needs their help. The Port Isaac Fundraising Team is linked to Port Isaac Lifeboat Station.

Keeping a modern fleet of lifeboats maintained, fuelled and ever ready to go to the rescue from all 33 South West lifeboat stations is expensive and we rely entirely on voluntary donations to ensure this service is maintained. Add to that crew training and kit, and the pounds start to add up. It costs an average of ¬£158k to Run lifeboat stations in the South West but this year, with the implications of Covid-19, we haven‚Äôt been able to fundraise to keep our lifeboats afloat.

We rely on donations from you the public to continue saving lives at sea - your donation to this page will help support the running costs of stations in the South West including our lifeboat based in Port Isaac and its volunteer crew.

Name: Port Isaac RNLI Lifesavers Fund

pageSummaryWhat: In loving memory of Edward Hartwell (d 30/4/2020)
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Edward  Hartwell
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

Like so many during the Covid crisis our father's farewell was attended only by immediate family and his Celebration of Life has had to be cancelled because of the ongoing restrictions. We are sorry that like so many thousands of others we have not been able to give him a 'proper' farewell. If you would like to make a donation in his memory we know he would be very pleased. Thank you.¬†

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

pageSummary: We are hosting an online Easter Fair because Morecambe needs the Lifeboat regularly
pageSummaryWhat: We are hosting an online Easter Fair
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
The RNLI has been operating at full capacity since the start of lockdown. Our service has been rescuing people throughout the Coronavirus pandemic and our heroic crews commitment to saving lives has not stopped. Unfortunately, our ability to raise funds has been limited.
The average lifeboat station in the North West costs ¬£136,000 a year to run and we are going to have a significant shortfall in income due to the Coronavirus. We are asking all our friends and communities to donate what they can to keep us running.
All along the North West coast from Silloth to West Kirby, we will always be there to keep you and your loved ones safe, on our watch, there will be no preventable deaths on the North West coast. Please help us fulfil that mission.

story:
So with lockdown restrictions hopefully coming to an end, I decided to throw myself into another 26.2 mile challenge, this time in aid of WWF...that‚Äôs the World Wildlife Fund, not the wrestlers.

This will be my 5th Marathon and my aim is to finish in under 4 hours. I know that by running for ‚ÄúTeam Panda‚Äù I‚Äôll be desperate to reach the finishing line as quickly as possible, inspired by the amazing work that they do to help protect endangered animals and generally attempt to sustain our planet (see below).

Any and all donations would be very gratefully received, and just think...while you‚Äôre all enjoying the reopening of the pubs this summer. I‚Äôll be enduring gruelling training runs and a calorie controlled diet. That has to be worth at least a sympathy donation...

Kev

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Last year Sophie wished for donations to Prostrate Cancer instead of birthday presents because her Grandfather had just finished his treatment journey. She raised ¬£250.¬†¬†

This year she has set her self a challenge to run 100km in the month of February. Her aim is 25km a week (5 days of 5km). As you know she is a determined girl and she is putting so much effort in. She is still going out when it is wet and cold and we are so proud of her.

She danced and whooped with delight when her grandparents, relatives and friends received their Covid vaccine and she wants others "to feel this happiness and be safe" (her words).¬†

So she is really hoping she can raise some money to support people in countries that don't have the funding to achieve it without help.¬†

Thanks for supporting¬†her and when this is all over she will give you all a big hug. In the meantime she is sending a virtual squeeze...‚Ä¶hope you can feel it!!

Here is some facts Sophie wanted to include that she has found on the UNICEF¬†website. Vaccines cost between ¬£1.50 and ¬£20 per dose but there are other costs too. ¬£63 will cover the transport cost of 4,205 doses of the vaccine. It costs ¬£45 to provide cold chain equipment to store 500 doses of the vaccine.¬†¬†

Join Unicef‚Äôs critical mission

The plan is ambitious. The scale and speed ‚Äì unprecedented.

Covid-19 is the biggest global crisis since World War Two. And children won‚Äôt be safe until everyone they rely on is safe.

With your support, Unicef will deliver 2 billion Covid-19 vaccines for health workers and the most high risk people on our planet.

From buying and transporting supplies through to administering the vaccine, you‚Äôll help deliver history. Your donation will ensure:

  • vaccines get to even the most remote places in the world
  • vaccines are safely stored using cold chain equipment
  • health workers are protected and trained to vaccinate their communities

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

We are so grateful that we have either had, or soon will have, a free Covid-19 vaccination course from our brilliant NHS.

So now we want to help enable the most vulnerable around the world to have the same protection by gifting a vaccine.¬†

Unicef is a leading partner in the Global COVAX Facility, and plans to¬†deliver 2 billion Covid-19 vaccines for health workers and the most high risk people on our planet. But they need our support.

From buying and transporting supplies through to administering the vaccine, our donations will help deliver history. Donations will ensure that¬†vaccines get to even the most remote places in the world,¬†that¬†vaccines are safely stored using cold chain equipment and that¬†health workers are protected and trained to vaccinate their communities.

More information about Unicef's role is here:¬†

https://www.unicef.org/supply/ensuring-global-equitable-access-covid-19-health-supplies-unicefs-role-act-acovax


Depending on type, the two Covid 19 vaccinations we receive from the NHS cost between ¬£6 - ¬£30. In addition to this is the cost of administering the injections.

Thank you so much for considering a donation, however small or large, to say thank you and to help the vulnerable around the world.

charity.description: Malaria No More UK mobilises governments, influencers, businesses and the public to end deaths from malaria and wipe out the disease for good. Our mission is to catalyse and inspire the global partnerships, leadership and financing to make malaria no more in a generation.
charity.name: MALARIA NO MORE UK
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story: In 2019 it is estimated that 409,000 people around the world died from malaria - a preventable disease - the majority being children under five and pregnant women (source: WHO). 2021 is a vital year in the global campaign to make our world one without malaria. This coming June, the Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting and the vitally important Kigali Summit on malaria and neglected tropical diseases will take place in Rwanda. The summit marks a historic moment that will unite global leaders and put a spotlight on the importance of renewed action in fighting malaria. We need more action, more innovation, more funding and more political leadership to defeat malaria and move forward stronger in this new global health landscape. Across Rentokil Initial, colleagues are taking part in a 9,000km Race to Kigali (the distance between our HQ and Kigali, Rwanda), including teams from America, Australia, Asia, Europe, the Middle East, Caribbean, Africa, HR, IT, Finance, M&A and Legal. By combining the efforts of colleagues walking, running or cycling, each team will ‚Äòreach‚Äô the distance to Kigali. This is our global effort to raise funds and show our support for this vital cause. It all starts on Monday 15 February through to the UN‚Äôs World Malaria Day on 25 April. Andy Ransom: "As a proud patron of Malaria No More UK, I am asking my colleagues at Rentokil Initial, as well as friends, family and associates to get involved in the Race to Kigali. In doing so, helping raise incredibly important funding for Malaria No More UK at such a critical time. Rentokil Initial Cares, our charitable fund, will match every ¬£1 raised up to ¬£100,000.‚Äù Together we can achieve a Zero Malaria world within a generation. Please show your support.

eventName: Access' Manchester to Madagascar - 5,777 miles for WaterAid! run by WaterAid
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
From Manchester to Madagascar 

From 15th February, well be walking, running, cycling, rowing and swimming to travel the 5,777 miles between Manchester to Madagascar, all in aid of highlighting WaterAid's work in Antenanarivo, Madagascar.

5,777 miles might take us a while to complete, so we are going to compete in two teams and start at each end - one team in Manchester and one team in Madagascar - and the objective is to meet in the middle by Easter, and see who gets there first!

Well be walking, running, cycling, rowing or even swimming (when allowed!) to help contribute individually and virtually to the 5,777 miles we need to complete together. 

The objective is to improve all our wellbeing, get us all out more in the fresh air and away from our computers, and to raise ¬£5,777 for a truly magnificent cause!

charity.name: WaterAid
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story: I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.

story:
Our team is taking up the challenge to walk 4km, 8km or 12km a day this March so that we can raise funds to help make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere.¬†¬† These distances reflect a walk that millions of women and girls around the world have to take each day to get the water they and their families need to survive.

Clean¬†water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone‚Äôs¬†daily life. Without all three, people can‚Äôt live dignified, healthy lives. With¬†all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change¬†their lives for good.

Thankyou so much for your support!

Deena, Greg, Liz and Tracy
